        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1972-12-27T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1968-12-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="291" subtype="editorial-note"
                type="document" xml:id="d291">
                <head>291. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>Documentation on participation of the Department of State and Secretary of State
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWP1">Rogers</persName> in the National Security
                    Council system is in the chapter on the <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>
                    system. Included is documentation on <persName corresp="#p_RWP1"
                        >Rogers</persName>’ relationships with President Nixon and <persName
                        corresp="#p_KHA1">Henry</persName>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> and on the views and concerns
                    expressed both in the White House and the Department of State about the
                    functioning of the <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> system and the respective
                    roles of the two agencies in shaping foreign policy. Documentation on foreign
                    economic policy, including the Department of State’s conflict with the
                    Department of Commerce over control of U.S. foreign economic and commercial
                    functions, is in the chapter on foreign economic policy. For documentation on
                    the President’s efforts to restructure the foreign assistance program, see <ref
                        target="frus1969-76v04#d1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1969–1976, volume IV, Foreign
                        Assistance, International Development, Trade Policies, 1969–1972, Documents
                        1</ref>–<ref target="frus1969-76v04#d147">147</ref>.</p>
            </div>
